<section class="materials reveal">
    <div class="container">
        <span class="small-tag">Tools & Medium</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">Materials I Use in My Drawing Process</h2>

        <div class="materials-grid">

            <!-- CHARCOAL -->
            <div class="material-card">
                <h3>Charcoal Drawing Materials (Full Breakdown)</h3>

                <p>
                    Charcoal is one of the most expressive and emotionally powerful mediums I work with.
                    It allows me to create extreme contrast, soft transitions, and deep realism that feels almost photographic.
                    My charcoal process is not random — it is controlled through different grades and forms of charcoal, each with a specific purpose.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Vine Charcoal (Soft Light Base):</b><br><br>
                    Vine charcoal is the lightest form of charcoal and is made from burnt wood sticks.
                    It is extremely soft, dusty, and easy to erase, which makes it perfect for early construction.
                    I use it in the beginning stage of every portrait to map out proportions, facial structure, and positioning.
                    It allows me to sketch freely without damaging the paper or committing to permanent marks.
                    It also helps me adjust mistakes easily while building the foundation of the drawing.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Compressed Charcoal (Deep Darkness & Contrast):</b><br><br>
                    Compressed charcoal is much darker, denser, and more permanent than vine charcoal.
                    It is made by compressing powdered charcoal into solid sticks.
                    I use it for building deep shadows such as hair mass, eye sockets, nostrils, and background dark areas.
                    This material is responsible for dramatic contrast and strong visual depth.
                    However, it must be controlled carefully because it is difficult to erase once applied.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Charcoal Pencils (Precision & Detail Control):</b><br><br>
                    Charcoal pencils are my main detailing tool.
                    Unlike loose charcoal, they are encased in wood and can be sharpened into fine points.
                    I use them for eyelashes, eyebrow strands, lip textures, wrinkles, and hair strands.
                    They allow me to switch between soft shading and sharp detailing with full control.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Soft Charcoal (Mid Tone Blending):</b><br><br>
                    Soft charcoal is used for smooth mid-tone transitions.
                    It helps in areas like cheeks, neck, and skin shading where harsh lines must be avoided.
                    It is essential for building natural-looking skin gradients.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Extra Soft Charcoal (Smooth Realism Layer):</b><br><br>
                    This is the lightest controlled charcoal tone.
                    It is used to create ultra-soft shading and skin-like smoothness.
                    It helps simulate natural lighting on skin surfaces.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Blending Stumps, Tissue & Cotton:</b><br><br>
                    These are essential for achieving realism.
                    Blending stumps smooth graphite and charcoal into the paper surface.
                    Tissue and cotton are used for larger blending areas like cheeks and backgrounds.
                    They remove harsh transitions and create cinematic smooth shading.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Kneaded Eraser:</b><br><br>
                    This is not just an eraser but a drawing tool.
                    I use it to lift charcoal gently instead of removing it completely.
                    It is used for highlights in eyes, skin reflections, and light edges in hair.
                </p>
            </div>


            <!-- GRAPHITE -->
            <div class="material-card">
                <h3>Graphite Pencil Range (3H – 14B Full Explanation)</h3>

                <p>
                    Graphite is the backbone of structured realism in my drawings.
                    I use a full range from very hard (3H) to extremely soft (14B).
                    Each pencil plays a unique role in building depth, structure, and realism.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Hard Pencils (3H, 2H, H):</b><br><br>
                    These are very light pencils used for initial sketching.
                    They help construct proportions, facial structure, and guidelines.
                    They are clean, precise, and do not smudge easily.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>HB Pencil (Neutral Base):</b><br><br>
                    HB is the balance point between hard and soft graphite.
                    It is used for refining sketches and light shading transitions.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Soft Graphite (2B, 3B, 4B):</b><br><br>
                    These are the most commonly used pencils in my work.
                    2B is for light shading, 3B for mid tones, and 4B for deeper shadows.
                    They create smooth skin textures and natural realism.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Dark Graphite (5B, 6B, 7B):</b><br><br>
                    These pencils are used for strong shadows and contrast areas.
                    They are applied in hair, facial depth, and background dark zones.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Very Dark Graphite (8B – 10B):</b><br><br>
                    These create deep shadows and focal contrast.
                    They help push realism and depth in key portrait areas.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Extreme Graphite (11B – 14B):</b><br><br>
                    These are the darkest graphite tones.
                    They are used sparingly for the deepest blacks in hair, pupils, and dramatic shadows.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Monozero Mechanical Pencil System:</b><br><br>
                    The Monozero is a precision detailing tool used for ultra-fine lines.
                    It allows me to draw extremely thin strokes that normal pencils cannot achieve.
                    I use it for eyelashes, hair strands, fabric threads, and sharp facial details.
                    It provides consistent sharpness and does not require constant sharpening,
                    making it perfect for hyper-realistic detailing work.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Blending Tools:</b><br><br>
                    Blending stumps, cotton buds, and soft brushes are used to smooth graphite layers.
                    They help create seamless skin textures and remove harsh pencil marks.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Erasers:</b><br><br>
                    Both rubber and kneaded erasers are used for correction and highlighting.
                    They help create light reflections in eyes, nose, and skin highlights.
                </p>
            </div>


            <!-- BRUSHES -->
            <div class="material-card">
                <h3>Brushes & Physical Drawing Tools</h3>

                <p>
                    Brushes are essential for controlling texture, dust, and smoothness in my artwork.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Soft Large Brushes:</b><br><br>
                    Used to remove excess charcoal or graphite dust without damaging the artwork.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Medium Brushes:</b><br><br>
                    Used for controlled blending of mid-tone areas like skin and backgrounds.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <b>Fine Detail Brushes:</b><br><br>
                    Used for lifting highlights and refining edges in eyes, lips, and hair strands.
                </p>
            </div>


            <!-- PAPER -->
            <div class="material-card">
                <h3>Paper Type (Needle Point Textured Paper)</h3>

                <p>
                    I use high-quality needle point textured paper for all my drawings.
                    This paper has a slightly rough surface that holds charcoal and graphite effectively.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The texture allows multiple layers of shading without damaging the surface.
                    It enhances realism by breaking smooth shading slightly, making the artwork more natural.
                </p>

                <p>
                    It is ideal for hyper-realistic portraits where gradual layering is very important.
                </p>
            </div>


            <!-- DIGITAL -->
            <div class="material-card">
                <h3>Digital Drawing (ibis Paint X - Full Workflow)</h3>

                <p>
                    For digital artwork, I use ibis Paint X, a powerful mobile drawing application.
                    It allows me to replicate traditional drawing techniques digitally.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The most important feature is the layer system.
                    I separate sketch, shading, detailing, and highlights into different layers for full control.
                </p>

                <p>
                    I use custom brushes that mimic graphite and charcoal textures.
                    This helps maintain my traditional drawing style in digital form.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Blending tools in ibis Paint X help smooth tones just like real blending stumps.
                </p>

                <p>
                    I use digital drawing for sketches, client previews, corrections, and final polished artwork.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Overall, ibis Paint X gives me speed, precision, and flexibility while maintaining realism.
                </p>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>
</section>


