<section class="guide-section">
    <div class="container">

        <span class="small-tag">Guide</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">Helpful Guide for Your Portrait</h2>

        <div class="guide-wrapper">

            <!-- ITEM 1 -->
            <div class="guide-item">
                <div class="guide-header" onclick="toggleGuide(this)">
                    <h3>Choosing the right photo for your portrait</h3>
                    <span class="icon">+</span>
                </div>
                <div class="guide-content">
                    <p>
                        The quality of your portrait depends heavily on the reference photo you provide. 
                        A clear, high-resolution image allows me to capture the finest details such as 
                        facial expressions, eye reflections, hair texture, and skin tone variations.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Avoid blurry, dark, or heavily filtered images because they reduce accuracy and realism. 
                        The best photos are well-lit, taken in natural light, and show the face clearly without shadows covering important areas.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If possible, choose a photo where the subject is looking directly at the camera. 
                        This helps create stronger emotional connection in the final artwork and ensures facial symmetry is properly captured.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ITEM 2 -->
            <div class="guide-item">
                <div class="guide-header" onclick="toggleGuide(this)">
                    <h3>Choosing the right size for your portrait</h3>
                    <span class="icon">+</span>
                </div>
                <div class="guide-content">
                    <p>
                        The size of your portrait determines the level of detail and visual impact. 
                        Smaller sizes are perfect for simple gifts, while larger sizes allow for extreme realism and finer detailing.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If you want highly detailed work such as visible skin textures, individual hair strands, or complex backgrounds, 
                        larger paper sizes like A3 or A2 are recommended.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For budget-friendly or simple portraits, A4 size works well, especially for single subjects with minimal background. 
                        Always consider where the artwork will be displayed before choosing a size—bedroom walls, living rooms, or office spaces may require larger frames.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ITEM 3 -->
            <div class="guide-item">
                <div class="guide-header" onclick="toggleGuide(this)">
                    <h3>How to frame your pencil portrait</h3>
                    <span class="icon">+</span>
                </div>
                <div class="guide-content">
                    <p>
                        Framing is very important because it protects your artwork and enhances its beauty. 
                        A well-framed portrait not only preserves the drawing from dust and moisture but also gives it a professional, gallery-like appearance.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It is recommended to use a glass frame to protect the pencil drawing from smudging. 
                        Always include a small white or black border (mounting) between the artwork and the frame to make it stand out visually.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Avoid placing framed portraits under direct sunlight or humid environments, as this may affect the quality of the paper over time. 
                        Proper framing ensures your artwork lasts for many years as a timeless memory.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

    </div>
</section>



